photo.title: Pier 39 Sea Lions

description._content:
Pier 39 is a popular shopping area in San Francisco.  A great diversion from shopping is to see the sea lions on Pier 39's K-Dock.  There is a tiered viewing area, and it's really a treat to get to see them so close.  

The crowd watching the raft of sea lions 'hauling out.'

Coit Tower and the Transamerica Pyramid are in the background.

photo.title: Port of San Francisco - 1915

description._content:
100 years - Port of San Francisco

Designed by American architect A. Page Brown in the Beaux Arts style in 1892, the ferry building was completed in 1898. 

At its opening, it was the largest project undertaken in the city up to that time. Brown designed the clock tower after the 12th-century Giralda bell tower in Seville, Spain, and the entire length of the building on both frontages is based on an arched arcade.

photo.title: City By The Bay

description._content:
It's not my own city in the bay (Melbourne, Australia) but it's certainly the most famous city by the bay, just before sunset on a warm Autumn/Fall evening.

The Golden Gate Bridge frames the central business district and many Piers and Coit Tower are easily visible.

Golden Gate Park is to the right and Alcatraz stands alone to the left. In the distance the Bay Bridge crosses the bay towards Oakland.

photo.title: North view

description._content: Looking north from Coit Tower you can see Pier 39 jutting out into the bay, flanked by sailboats on the right and a sea lion colony on the left. Alcatraz Island sits in the middle of the bay, looking thinner from this vantage point. Angel Island State Park, another island I've never visited, lies beyond it on the right, and Marin County beyond that.

photo.title: Coit Tower from Chinese Cultural Center Chinatown in Hilton hotel San Francisco's Financial District 150307-132341 C4

description._content: Coit Tower is one of San Francisco's lesser known landmarks. Its 210 foot high tower of Art Deco design was built in the 1930s entirely of Federal Funds. In 1934, four women and twenty-one men covered the 3,641 feet of the interior walls with frescoes in the first publicly funded works of art project under the New Deal. Coit Tower is a prominent structure from various points of view near the Marina, North Beach, even from as far away as the Golden Gate Bridge, and across San Francisco Bay. During the 2015 Chinese Lunar Year Spring Festival, Melody and I visited the Chinese Cultural Center located in the Hilton Hotel Financial District. It was there we saw this view of Coit Tower from the south with the view obstructed only by the architecture of fancy Telegraph hill residential buildings. The streaks in the blue of the sky are residue on the outside of the thick windows of the hotel. A must shoot opportunity of this rare view anyway with my Canon Powershot SX50.

description._content:
Thank you, Lily Coit.  San Francisco.  October. 2015.

When I was 10 years-old (and living in LA), I read a story called "The Mystery On Telegraph Hill" in which the fog was normally so thick one could only see a few meters ahead; it made such an impression on me, that image, that every time I am able to see Telegraph Hill now, it feels like a miracle.
